# Part III — Weight Diagnostics

<div class="note-box">
**Reading the table.** `Sum_w ≈ 0` confirms translation invariance. `ESS = 1/Σωᵢ²` is effective sample size — **watch for very low ESS here**, especially the Kitagawa spec, where a weak first stage can drive ESS toward 1. `Pct_neg` = share of negative weights. `Max_abs_w` = largest single weight.
</div>

```{r diag-builder, echo=FALSE}
build_diag_table <- function(D, X_kappa) {
  p_ml  <- logit_mle(Z, X_kappa)
  p_cb  <- get_cbps_p(Z, X_kappa)
  kw_ml <- kappa_outcome_weights(Z, D, p_ml)
  kw_cb <- kappa_outcome_weights(Z, D, p_cb)

  rbind(
    weight_diag(kw_cb$w_u,   "τ_cb_u    (CBPS, norm)"),
    weight_diag(kw_ml$w_u,   "τ_ml_u    (MLE, norm)"),
    weight_diag(kw_ml$w_a10, "τ_ml_a10  (MLE, norm)"),
    weight_diag(kw_ml$w_a,   "τ_ml_a    (unnorm)"),
    weight_diag(kw_ml$w_a1,  "τ_ml_t    (unnorm)"),
    weight_diag(kw_ml$w_a0,  "τ_ml_a0   (unnorm)")
  )
}

style_diag <- function(df, cap) {
  df %>%
    kbl(caption = cap, align = c("l","r","r","r","r")) %>%
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped","hover","condensed"),
                  full_width = TRUE, font_size = 13) %>%
    footnote(general = "Sum_w ≈ 0 ⟺ translation invariant. ESS = 1/Σωᵢ². Low ESS = extreme weight concentration.")
}
```

